Patrick Lencioni (obviously) wrote The Five Dysfunctions of a Team.
In that book we learn that the five dysfunctions you need to avoid are &hellip;
Absence of trust — unwilling to be vulnerable within the group Fear of conflict — seeking artificial harmony over constructive passionate debate Lack of commitment — feigning buy-in for group decisions creates ambiguity throughout the organization Avoidance of accountability — ducking the responsibility to call peers, superiors on counterproductive behavior which sets low standards Inattention to team results — focusing on personal success, status and ego before team success I always try to frame these in positive/actionable terms by asking people to help me to build teams that show/exhibit the following characteristics &hellip;

Updated (2021-08-14): Added some test data (at the end; see below)
As I said before &hellip;
When you work from anywhere (or even from home) it is YOUR(!!!) responsibility to ensure that you are connected!!!
